\begin_layout Standard
A generalized combination network 
\begin_inset Formula $(\epsilon,l)-\mathcal{N}_{h,r,s}$
\end_inset

 consists of 3 components from top to bottom: 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Source
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 in the first layer, 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Node
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 in the middle layer, and 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Receiver
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 in the third layer.
 The network has a source with 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 messages, 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 nodes, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\begin{array}{c}
r\\
\alpha
\end{array}\right)$
\end_inset

 receivers, which form a single source multicast network modeled as a finite
 directed acyclic multigraph.
 The source connects to each node by 
\begin_inset Formula $l$
\end_inset

 parallel links and each node also connects to a receiver by 
\begin_inset Formula $l$
\end_inset

 parallel links, which are respectively called a node's incoming and outgoing
 edges.
 Each receiver is connected by 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 links in total, specifically 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha l$
\end_inset

 links from 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 nodes and 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon$
\end_inset

 direct links from the source, i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $s=\alpha l+\epsilon$
\end_inset

.
 The combination network in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Riis:2006"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 is the 
\begin_inset Formula $(0,1)-\mathcal{N}_{h,r,s}$
\end_inset

 network and the 
\begin_inset Formula $(1,1)-\mathcal{N}_{h,r,s}$
\end_inset

 network is called One-Direct Link Combination Network.
 Theorem 1 shows our interest of relations between the parameters 
\begin_inset Formula $h,\alpha,\epsilon$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $l$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "nw_parameters"

\end_inset

The 
\begin_inset Formula $(\epsilon,l)-\mathcal{N}_{h,r,s}$
\end_inset

 network has a trivial solution if 
\begin_inset Formula $l+\epsilon\geq h$
\end_inset

, and it has no solution if 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha l+\epsilon<h$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
Proof: Following to the network coding max-flow min-cut theorem for multicast
 networks, the maximum number of messages from the source to each receiver
 is equal to the smallest min-cut between the source and any receiver.
 For our considered network, 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 links have to be deleted to disconnect the source from the receiver, which
 implies that the min-cut between the source and each receiver is at least
 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

.
 Hence, 
\begin_inset Formula $h\leq s\Leftrightarrow h\leq\alpha l+\epsilon$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\Square$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
There exist at least 
\begin_inset Formula $l+\epsilon$
\end_inset

 disjoint links connected to each receiver.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $l+\epsilon\geq h$
\end_inset

, each receiver can always reconstruct its requested messages on its links.
 Then we only need to do routing to select paths for the network.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\Square$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Remark
Following to Theorem 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "nw_parameters"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, we are interested in this range: 
\begin_inset Formula $l+\epsilon+1\leq h\leq\alpha l+\epsilon$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Network coding for networks from this network family
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Scalar network coding
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A message is equivalent to a symbol over 
\begin_inset Formula $\ensuremath{\mathbb{F}}_{q_{s}}$
\end_inset

.
 As a network of the multicast model, all receivers request the same packet
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 symbols at the same time 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Trautmann:2013"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 A packet is a 1-dimentional subspace of 
\begin_inset Formula $\ensuremath{\mathbb{F}}_{q_{s}}^{h}$
\end_inset

; hence, each receiver must obtain a subspace of 
\begin_inset Formula $\ensuremath{\mathbb{F}}_{q_{s}}^{h}$
\end_inset

, whose dimension is at least 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

, to be able to reconstruct the packet.
 Through 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon$
\end_inset

 direct links connected from the source to a receiver, the source can provide
 any required 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon$
\end_inset

 1-dimensional subspaces of 
\begin_inset Formula $\ensuremath{\mathbb{F}}_{q_{s}}^{h}$
\end_inset

 for the corresponding receiver.
 Each receiver can accordingly reconstruct the packet if and only if the
 linear span of 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $l$
\end_inset

-dimensional subspaces of 
\begin_inset Formula $\ensuremath{\mathbb{F}}_{q_{s}}^{h}$
\end_inset

 from the nodes is at least of dimension 
\begin_inset Formula $h-\epsilon$
\end_inset

.
 When this necessary condition is satisfied, the network is said to have
 a 
\shape italic
solution
\shape default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
The 
\begin_inset Formula $(0,1)-\mathcal{N}_{h,r,s}$
\end_inset

 network has a solution if and only if there exists an 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(r,\left|\ensuremath{\mathbb{F}}_{q_{s}}\right|h,r-\alpha+1\right)$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\ensuremath{\mathbb{F}}_{q_{s}}\right|$
\end_inset

-ary error correcting code.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Riis:2006"
literal "false"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Vector network coding
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The messages are vectors of length 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $\ensuremath{\mathbb{F}}_{q}$
\end_inset

.
 Hence, a vector solution is over field size 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 and dimension 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

.
 Such a vector solution has the same alphabet size as a scalar solution
 of field size 
\begin_inset Formula $q^{t}$
\end_inset

, and we denote 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{v}=q^{t}$
\end_inset

.
 Similarly with the scalar 
\shape italic
linear
\shape default
 coding solution, each receiver can reconstruct its requested packet if
 and only if any 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(lt\right)$
\end_inset

-dimensional subspaces span a subspace of dimension at least 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(h-\epsilon\right)t$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
A vector solution for the 
\begin_inset Formula $(\epsilon,l)-\mathcal{N}_{h,r,s}$
\end_inset

 network exists if and only if there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{G}_{q}\left(ht,lt\right)$
\end_inset

 such that any 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 subspaces of the set span a subspace of dimension at least 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(h-\epsilon\right)t$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Zhang:2019"
literal "false"

\end_inset


\end_layout

