.
 Regarding to 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

, we have:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
d(r) & \leq & 3\cdot\left(\begin{array}{c}
r-1\\
2
\end{array}\right)=3\cdot\frac{\left(r-1\right)\left(r-2\right)}{2}=\frac{3}{2}\left(r^{2}-3r+2\right)=d_{1}(r)\\
 & \leq & \frac{3}{2}r^{2}=d_{2}(r)
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Hence, we have below implications:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
 & 4\cdot p\cdot d_{2}(r) & \leq1\\
\overset{1}{\Rightarrow} & 4\cdot p\cdot d_{1}(r) & \leq1\\
\overset{2}{\Rightarrow} & 4\cdot p\cdot d(r) & \leq1
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
1: 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{1}(r)\leq d_{2}(r)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
2: 
\begin_inset Formula $d(r)\leq d_{1}(r)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In consideration of 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{2}(r)$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
4\cdot p\cdot d_{2}(r)\leq1\Rightarrow4\cdot p\cdot\frac{3}{2}r^{2}\leq1\Rightarrow r\leq\sqrt{\frac{1}{6p}}=r_{max}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Similarly with above, 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 are propotional, so minimizing 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 is equivelent to maximizing 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 The purpose is to achieve a strict lower bound proving vector solutions
 always outperform scalar solutions in a specific range of 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

, i.e., 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{max}$
\end_inset

asymptotes to a value higher than 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{scalar}$
\end_inset

.
 Now, we begin to maximize 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 We consider the nominator of Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:p_eq_h3"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\stackrel[j=0]{i-1}{\mathop{\prod}}\frac{\left(q^{3t}-q^{j}\right)^{2}}{q^{i}-q^{j}}=\frac{p_{N}^{(i)}(q)}{p_{D}^{(i)}(q)}=p^{(i)}(q)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Due to 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

-times product and large 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left.\begin{array}{c}
deg\left(p_{N}^{(i)}(q)\right)=q^{i6t}\\
deg\left(p_{D}^{(i)}(q)\right)=q^{i^{2}}
\end{array}\right\} \Rightarrow p^{(i)}(q)\approx q^{i6t-i^{2}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Then we have:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\stackrel[i=1]{2t-1}{\mathop{\sum}}\stackrel[j=0]{i-1}{\mathop{\prod}}\frac{\left(q^{3t}-q^{j}\right)^{2}}{q^{i}-q^{j}}=\stackrel[i=1]{2t-1}{\mathop{\sum}}p^{(i)}(q)\approx\stackrel[i=1]{2t-1}{\mathop{\sum}}q^{i6t-i^{2}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To maximize the sum, we set derivation of to 0 and find its root:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
 & \left(i6t-i^{2}\right)^{'} & =0\\
\Leftrightarrow & 6t-2i & =0\\
\Leftrightarrow & i & =3t
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
However, the upper limit of sum is 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(2t-1\right)$
\end_inset

, which is less than 
\begin_inset Formula $3t$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Rightarrow max\left\{ q^{i6t-i^{2}}:i=1,2\ldots,2t-1\right\} =\left.q^{i6t-i^{2}}\right|_{i=2t-1}=q^{8t^{2}-2t-1}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Hence, by using the exact bound 
\begin_inset Formula $\Theta$
\end_inset

, we have:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\stackrel[i=1]{2t-1}{\mathop{\sum}}p^{(i)}(q)\in\Theta\left(max\left\{ q^{i6t-i^{2}}:i=1,2\ldots,2t-1\right\} \right)=\Theta\left(q^{8t^{2}-2t-1}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Rightarrow\frac{1+\stackrel[i=1]{2t-1}{\mathop{\sum}}p^{(i)}(q)}{q^{9t^{2}}}\approx\frac{\stackrel[i=1]{2t-1}{\mathop{\sum}}p^{(i)}(q)}{q^{9t^{2}}}\in\Theta\left(q^{-t^{2}-2t-1}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Finally, we have:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
r_{max}\in\Omega\left(\sqrt{\frac{1}{6p}}\right)=\Omega\left(\sqrt{\frac{1}{6q^{-t^{2}-2t-1}}}\right)=\Omega\left(q^{t^{2}/2+\mathcal{O}\left(t\right)}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Further we have: 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{max,scalar}\in\mathcal{O}\left(q_{s}^{2}\right)$
\end_inset

 
